<paragraph id="P-0023" lvl="0"><number>&lsqb;0023&rsqb;</number> The receiver, thus, has to maximize &Lgr;A(&Lgr;*)<highlight><superscript>T</superscript></highlight>, subject to the constraint &par;&Lgr;&par;<highlight><superscript>2</superscript></highlight>&equals;1. The solution to this problem is to choose &Lgr; to be the eigenvector of A which corresponds to the maximum eigenvalue of A. Accordingly, processor <highlight><bold>45</bold></highlight> develops the matrix A from the values of &agr;<highlight><subscript>ij</subscript></highlight>, finds the eigenvalues of A in a conventional manner, selects the maximum eigenvalue of A, and creates the vector &Lgr;. Once A is known, processor <highlight><bold>45</bold></highlight> develops signals &ggr;<highlight><subscript>i </subscript></highlight>for 1&equals;1, 2, 3, . . . , n, (where  
